<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1872-06-11T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1872-06-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="237" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d237">
                        <head>No. 102.<lb/><hi rend="italic">General <persName type="from">Schenck</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Fish</persName></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1872-06-11"><hi rend="italic">June</hi> 11, 1872</date>.
                                (Received at 3.40 p.m.)</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Have acknowledged Lord Granville’s note telegraphed you this morning,
                            saying I have transmitted it to my Government, at Washington, where I
                            have no doubt it will be received and considered in the same friendly
                            spirit in which it is intended, and as a sincere effort yet to preserve
                            the Treaty between the two countries.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>SCHENCK.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>